{
  "texts": [
    "Recent advances in Large Language Models (LLMs) have shown their remarkable capabilities in various domains, including but not limited to math and code reasoning (Guo et al., 2025; Chen et al., 2021; Yang et al., 2024; Huang and Yang, 2025), interactive tool usage (Team et al., 2025; Wang et al., 2025), and conversational agents (Ouyang et al., 2022; Achiam et al., 2023; Comanici et al., 2025; Grattafiori et al., 2024).",
    "Among these capabilities, instruction-following (IF) is arguably one of the most fundamental focuses of LLM development as it underlies agents' ability to generalize to novel tasks and translate user intent into desired outputs (Ouyang et al., 2022; Wei et al., 2021).",
    "While contemporary LLMs can already follow direct and simple instructions quite well, they are still struggling to deal with users' complex instructions, which is quite common and challenging, as the instructions may contain multiple user intentions spanned over different turns of the conversation (He et al., 2024; Deshpande et al., 2025).",
    "Meanwhile, Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards (RLVR) has become a powerful post-training technique to improve LLMs' reasoning capabilities on math and code tasks, where the model's generations can be easily scored by matching the final answers of math problems or unit tests for programming (Guo et al., 2025; Yu et al., 2025; Luo et al., 2025; Lin et al., 2025).",
    "However, RLVR cannot be applied directly to improve LLMs' IF capabilities, as it is non-trivial to verify whether a model's response fully follows a user's instructions, especially for the hard ones."
  ]
}